# TypeScript standards

- Strict mode on (`tsconfig` `strict: true`). No implicit `any`. An
  explicit `any` needs a `// eslint-disable` (or equivalent) comment
  explaining why it's unavoidable, not a silent escape hatch.
- Exported functions declare an explicit return type — don't rely on
  inference at the public boundary, even where TypeScript could work
  it out.
- Named exports only, no `export default` — keeps renames and
  cross-package refactors mechanical instead of ambiguous.
- Keep `packages/` framework-agnostic where it can be. The React-vs-Solid
  choice (`docs/00-index-and-vision.md`, open question) stays isolated
  to `apps/` and `@gridyard/ui-kit` — don't let it leak into
  `@gridyard/grid-renderer`'s core rendering logic or
  `@gridyard/workspace-runtime`'s layout/permission logic.
- Prefer returning new values over mutating arguments in place,
  especially anywhere touching workspace schema objects — mutation
  there is an easy source of bugs once permission/layout inheritance
  (`docs/04-layout-and-permission-engine-spec.md`) is implemented.

## Unit tests

Every exported function or class ships a colocated `<file>.test.ts`
next to the file it tests, using Vitest. Cover the happy path and at
least one edge case (empty input, a boundary value, or an error path).

See `packages/grid-renderer/src/index.test.ts` for the pattern this
repo follows.
